The Krettly Quartet was a French string quartet musical ensemble active during the 1920s and 1930s. Its repertoire included avant-garde and modern works, and the group made early recordings of some of these. 1st violin 2nd violin viola 'cello The quartet took its name from the leader, the violinist Robert Krettly (b. 1891), who was brother of the cellist Odette Krettly (one of the teachers of Pierre Fournier (19061986)). Robert Krettly took part in the premiere of the Gabriel Faur Pianoforte Trio in D minor op 120, in Paris on May 12, 1923, with Jacques Patt (cello) and Tatiana Sanzvitch (piano).[1] The quartet was in existence in March 1925, with Fournier as its cellist aged 19, when they premiered the string quartet by Catherine Murphy Urner at the Salle Pleyel, Paris.[2] This formation therefore preceded the appearance of Robert Krettly as second violin, with Jacques Thibaud (1st violin), Maurice Vieux (18841951) (viola) and Andr Hekking (cello),[3] in the premiere of the Gabriel Faur string quartet (in E minor, op 121) at the Socit Nationale de Musique in Paris on 12 June 1925.[4] Fournier had also studied with Andr Hekking, and with Lucien Capet. In 1929 Andre Navarra (19111988) replaced Pierre Fournier as cellist,[5] and by 1931 Franois Broos had replaced Georges Taine at the viola desk. Navarra made his debut as a soloist in 1931, at the Concerts Colonne in Paris. Both Navarra and Ren Costard retired from the group in 1935, and in that year Costard established the French branch of Foldex maps.[6] The Krettly Quartet made some significant recordings before 1936, including principally:[7] 
